I took a look at TabletTime and it does not seem like a good fit because it also has functionality for tracking a tablets current time.  This tracking code is used by tablets as they processing incoming mutations.  The tracking code makes TabletTime mutable.  

I think it would be better to have a much simpler immutable POJO that represents the information stored in the metadata table.  Something like

```java
public class MetadataTime {
  private final TimeType type;
  private final long time;

  // TODO constructor, getters, hashcode, equals
}
```

Tablet time could be modified so that its constructed using this new POJO.

I would argue in favor of small classes rather than an enum, for the following reasons:

1. It allows us to organize actions in a type hierarchy with abstract base classes to group them together (not possible with Enums).
2. It allows users to define their own actions in their own code if they want to.
3. It makes our code a bit more extensible if we want to add more actions ourselves.

Example:

```java
interface Action {
  String description();
}

public abstract class TableAction {
  // note these are inner-classes to keep things organized
  public static class Split extends TableAction {
    // ...
  }
  public static class Scan extends TableAction {
    // ...
  }
  // ...
}

```

Some of these actions could be constructed with additional state information (like table name) that can be used to help a policy engine determine whether the action can be performed or not.

I'm considering the following update to TimeType and suggest using this instead of the single character checks for 'M' and 'L' in different places.  Note that 'code' may not be the best name, maybe 'id' which is used in 'LOGICAL_TIME_ID' or 'prefix'.
```java
/**
 * The type of ordering to use for the table's entries (default is MILLIS)
 */
public enum TimeType {
  /**
   * Used to guarantee ordering of data sequentially as inserted
   */
  LOGICAL('L'),

  /**
   * This is the default. Tries to ensure that inserted data is stored with the timestamp closest to
   * the machine's time to the nearest millisecond, without going backwards to guarantee insertion
   * sequence. Note that using this time type can cause time to "skip" forward if a machine has a
   * time that is too far off. NTP is recommended when using this type.
   */
  MILLIS('M');

  public final char code;

  /**
   * Parses a char code into a TimeType - like valueOf on name
   * 
   * @param code
   * @return type matching code or null if not found
   */
  public static TimeType valueOfCode(char code) {
    for (TimeType type : values()) {
      if (type.code == code)
        return type;
    }
    return null;
  }

  /**
   * Enum constructor
   * 
   * @param code
   */
  private TimeType(char code) {
    this.code = code;
  }

}
```

@hkeebler I really like the proposed changes to TimeType, however TimeType is in the public API and the code is an internal implementation detail best left out of the public API.  I am not sure where to put it, but we should have an internal static method that is similar to the valueOfCode method.  Maybe something like

```java
package some non api package;

class TimeTypeImpl {
  public static TimeType valueOf(char code) {
     switch(code) {
        case 'M':
             return TimeType.MILLIS;
        case 'L':
              return TimeType.LOGICAL;
         default:
             throw new IllegalArgumentException("Unknown time type code : "+code);
     }
  }
}
```

I added it as a static method to MetadataTime.  I think that works (??)  It's in core which is used by most every other module.
```java
package org.apache.accumulo.core.metadata.schema;

import org.apache.accumulo.core.client.admin.TimeType;

public class MetadataTime {
  private long time;
  private TimeType type; // default type is M for milliseconds

  public MetadataTime(long time) {
    this(time, TimeType.MILLIS);
  }

  public MetadataTime(long time, TimeType type) {
    this.time = time;
    this.type = type;
  }

  public MetadataTime(String timestr) throws Exception {
    if (timestr != null && timestr.length() > 1) {
      type = valueOf(timestr.charAt(0));
      time = Long.parseLong(timestr.substring(1));
    } else
      throw new IllegalArgumentException("Unknown metadata time value " + timestr);
  }

  /**
   * Converts timetypes to data codes used in the table data implementation
    * @param code
   * @return TimeType represented by code.
   */
  public static TimeType valueOf(char code) {
    switch(code) {
      case 'M':
        return TimeType.MILLIS;
      case 'L':
        return TimeType.LOGICAL;
      default:
        throw new IllegalArgumentException("Unknown time type code : "+code);
    }
  }

  /**
   * @return the single char code of this objects timeType
   */
  public char getCode(){
    switch(this.type) {
      case MILLIS:
        return 'M';
      case LOGICAL:
        return 'L';
      default:
        return 'M';
    }
  }
  public TimeType getType() {
    return type;
  }

  public void setType(TimeType type) {
    this.type = type;
  }

  public long getTime() {
    return time;
  }

  public void setTime(long time) {
    if (time < 0)
      throw new IllegalArgumentException();
    this.time = time;
  }

  @Override
  public boolean equals(Object o) {
    if (o instanceof MetadataTime) {
      MetadataTime t = (MetadataTime) o;
      return time == t.getTime() && type == t.getType();
    }
    return false;
  }

  @Override
  public int hashCode() {
    return 31 * ((31 * Long.valueOf(time).hashCode()) + (31 * type.hashCode()));
  }

  @Override
  public String toString() {
    return "" + getCode() + time;
  }


}
```

Wrote the following test to stress test the LinkingIterator while researching this issue.  The test runs continually scanning the metadata table while a table is splitting.  This is to look for issues where the linking iterator does not handle split properly.  It did find one issue.  Not sure what to do with the test thought as it just runs for a long time.

```java
public class TmpIT extends AccumuloClusterHarness {

  @Override
  public int defaultTimeoutSeconds() {
    return 30;
  }

  @Test
  public void test() throws Exception {

    for (int i = 0; i < 1000; i++) {
      testScanWhileSplitting();
      System.out.println("I " + i);
    }
  }

  private void testScanWhileSplitting() throws AccumuloSecurityException, AccumuloException,
      TableExistsException, TableNotFoundException {
    Random rand = new Random();

    List<Text> initialSplits = new ArrayList<>();

    int initSize = rand.nextInt(1990) + 10;
    for (int i = 0; i < initSize; i++) {
      initialSplits.add(new Text(String.format("%016x", rand.nextLong())));
    }

    Collections.sort(initialSplits);

    // call the batchwriter with buffer of size zero
    String table = getUniqueNames(1)[0];
    try (AccumuloClient c = Accumulo.newClient().from(getClientProps()).build()) {

      ExecutorService es = Executors.newFixedThreadPool(1);

      NewTableConfiguration ntc = new NewTableConfiguration();
      ntc.withSplits(new TreeSet<>(initialSplits));
      c.tableOperations().create(table, ntc);

      String id = c.tableOperations().tableIdMap().get(table);

      Future<Void> splitFuture = es.submit(() -> {
        List<Text> nextSplits = new ArrayList<>();
        int nextsize = rand.nextInt(1990) + 10;
        for (int i = 0; i < nextsize; i++) {
          nextSplits.add(new Text(String.format("%016x", rand.nextLong())));
        }

        c.tableOperations().addSplits(table, new TreeSet<Text>(nextSplits));
        return null;
      });

      do {
        // TODO in LoadFiles following called overlapping() while building
        Iterator<TabletMetadata> tabletIter = TabletsMetadata.builder().forTable(TableId.of(id))
            .checkConsistency().fetchPrev().fetchLocation().fetchLoaded().build(c).iterator();

        ArrayDeque<Text> splits = new ArrayDeque<Text>(initialSplits);

        Text prev = null;

        while (tabletIter.hasNext() && !splits.isEmpty()) {
          Text split = splits.removeFirst();
          KeyExtent extent = tabletIter.next().getExtent();

          Assert.assertEquals(prev, extent.getPrevEndRow());

          while (extent.getEndRow().compareTo(split) < 0) {
            prev = extent.getEndRow();
            extent = tabletIter.next().getExtent();
            Assert.assertEquals(prev, extent.getPrevEndRow());
          }

          prev = extent.getEndRow();

          Assert.assertEquals(split, extent.getEndRow());
        }

        while (tabletIter.hasNext()) {
          KeyExtent extent = tabletIter.next().getExtent();
          Assert.assertEquals(prev, extent.getPrevEndRow());
          prev = extent.getEndRow();

          if (extent.getEndRow() == null) {
            Assert.assertFalse(tabletIter.hasNext());
          }
        }

        Assert.assertTrue(splits.isEmpty());

        // System.out.println("Finished a pass");

      } while (!splitFuture.isDone());

      es.shutdown();

      c.tableOperations().delete(table);
    }
  }

}

```

@ctubbsii perhaps this issue then could be as simple as adding a way to determine the settings for a specified tserver to the config shell command.

This brings up another issue in that currently our cluster is likely running in a state where many zk mutable properties have been changed. In order to just use separate config files, we would have to go through and scrub for those and ensure every set property is in the configs appropriately (at least for those that are tserver related). Granted, this is our problem, not accumulo's.

It also seems to me that not having a mechanism for dealing with this in the config shell commands leads to ambiguous behavior, or at least changes what the intuitive definition of "site" is. For instance, when connected to one tserver, would config -f <property> output that value in that tservers configuration under the "site" layer? That leads me, as the user, to believe that is for this entire accumulo instance, but that is not the case.
